What is the RI DataHUB?

The Rhode Island DataHUB, initially created in conjunction with the RI Department of Education as the Statewide Longitudinal Data System (SLDS) for Rhode Island, connects data across sectors to support research and analysis that informs policy making and program evaluation to improve the well-being of all Rhode Islanders.

The Rhode Island DataHUB, initially created in conjunction with the RI Department of Education as the Statewide Longitudinal Data System (SLDS) for Rhode Island,
connects data across sectors to support research and analysis that informs policy making and program evaluation to improve the well-being of all Rhode Islanders.

What is the RI DataHUB?

The Rhode Island DataHUB, initially created in conjunction with the RI Department of Education
as the Statewide Longitudinal Data System (SLDS) for Rhode Island,
connects data across sectors to support research and analysis that informs
policy making and program evaluation to improve the well-being of all Rhode Islanders.

How can I work with the RIDataHUB?

Requests/Overview content

There are three main ways to work with the RI DataHUB.

  • Partner with DataSpark to complete an analysis.
  • Request aggregated, suppressed data.
  • Apply for access to individual-level, de-identified data.

Data use requires the permission of the individual state agencies who own the data. DataSpark can help you navigate the process of obtaining authorization to use DataHUB data.

How can I work with the RIDataHUB?

How can I work with the RI Datahub?

There are three main ways to work with the RI DataHUB.

  • Partner with DataSpark to complete an analysis.
  • Request aggregated, suppressed data.
  • Apply for access to individual-level, de-identified data.

Data use requires the permission of the individual state agencies who own the data. DataSpark can help you navigate the process of obtaining authorization to use DataHUB data.

Who runs the RIDataHUB?

Who runs the RIDataHUB?

The RIDataHUB is built and maintained by DataSpark, a program unit at the University of Rhode Island (URI). Day-to-day operation of the DataHUB, including data preparation, import, linkage, and quality reporting is managed by the DataSpark team.

However, data in the DataHUB belongs to the partner agencies, not to DataSpark or URI. Therefore, the oversight of the DataHUB and decisions around data use and access falls to a governance board made up of representatives of these partner agencies.

What is the datahub?

System/Overview content

The RI DataHUB is a persistent, holistic, integrated data system operated out of the University of Rhode Island. It is designed to continually take in administrative data from partner state agencies, link data across disparate sources, and provide de-identified request-ready data to approved researchers.

The DataHUB currently has 21 collections of data from 18 sources including multiple state agencies, local governments, and independent non-profits. Learn more about our data holdings

What research is done with the RIDataHUB?

Research/Overview content

DataSpark’s primary objectives for the DataHUB are:

  • to maintain continuously linked datasets for use by researchers and state agencies,
  • to generate analyses and reports using those datasets for policymakers, and
  • to support research and analysis for the public good.

See current and past research projects created using the RIDataHUB.

fields.title: Project
fields.content:
POSTSECONDARY OUTCOMES FOR RHODE ISLAND WORKFORCE TRAINING PARTICIPANTS

This analysis focuses on workforce training program participants and their entry into postsecondary education. It assesses participants by the timing of their postsecondary enrollment and their training exit type and determines how many participants enter fields of study that are preparatory for the same industries they accessed in their workforce training program.

Sources: RIOPC, RI DLT 10 April, 2020
HEALTH GRADS IN THE RI WORKFORCE

What is the employment landscape for health field graduates from RI's public higher education system?

Sources: RI DLT 10 April, 2020
ADULT LEARNERS IN RI'S WORKFORCE

Adult education programs are designed to provide adults at many levels of learning with the skills they need to provide for themselves and their families, advance their job prospects, and contribute to the general welfare of the state.

To discover the extent to which adult education in Rhode Island achieves these goals, we examine the impact of adult ed participation on learners’ ability to obtain and retain employment and to increase their earning capacity.

Sources: RI DLT 10 April, 2020

fields.title: System Overview
fields.content:
How It Works?

Under data sharing agreements that the University of Rhode Island and its program unit, DataSpark, have established with partner agencies and organizations, we integrate individual-level data on wages, unemployment, early childhood, K-12 and higher education, criminal justice, and health and human services into the system.

These administrative records are collected on an ongoing basis by our partners and are updated by DataSpark at regular intervals. The updating process entails collaboration between agency data stewards and DataSpark staff to ensure that data are clean, that changes or additions are well-understood, and that knowledge about underlying programs and policies is incorporated. These collaborations are essential to ensuring that the data are accurate, allowing staff and researchers to use the data without additional vetting or quality checking. The data are linked by an algorithm that DataSpark has developed and refined over the decade of the DataHUB’s existence, and are then de-identified for analytic use.

fields.title: Governance Overview
fields.content:
What is data governance?

Data governance refers to the overall management of SLDS data, including its availability, usability, integrity, quality, and security. It is the means by which organizations (or groups of organizations) make decisions about their collective information assets.

Implementing data governance can help

create a common vision for strategic and more effective data use

align policy and research questions with agency or state priorities and initiatives

improve data quality and protect data privacy

develop well-defined, documented data policies and priorities

coordinate among partner agencies on data integration and use

improve understanding of data collected, reported, and used

improve communication, collaboration, and relationships among partner agencies

The RI DataHUB Data Governance Board was convened in 2019 with representation from DataHUB-participating agencies and the Governor’s Office. The Board replaces the former DataHUB Advisory Council, which existed when the DataHUB was part of Providence nonprofit, The Providence Plan

See our policies and processes or learn about federal guidance on data governance

fields.title: Research Overview
fields.content:
Support Government Agencies

The RI DataHUB has partnered with many state and local government agencies across Rhode Island to help support programs and inform decision-making. DataSpark partners with the state based on the services needed and has undertaken state work as a research subgrantee and as a data services vendor. Data Stories resulting from some of these partnerships are viewable at ridatahub.org/datastories.

DataSpark’s work using the RI DataHUB is always driven by state priorities and is either commissioned by the state or undertaken with state approval. Learn more about data use oversight.

Support Research in Institutions of Higher Education

Linked, de-identified data from the RI DataHUB can be used by approved researchers under strict security and confidentiality requirements and agency consent. DataSpark works with researchers who have proposed an analysis that aligns with state research priorities. DataSpark staff help researchers understand how to translate the DataHUB’s administrative data into the analytic data. If proposed analyses are approved by agency data providers, DataSpark contracts with researchers to prepare and securely transmit the requested data for use during the approved project period.

Past and current projects have included research on the economic and social impact of Adult Education Programs in Rhode Island, research on the labor market outcomes to workforce training programs, research on the association between childhood lead exposure and later school outcomes, and research on the postsecondary outcomes to K-12 career and technical education.

Enable Cross-Agency Data Integration

[note: this section is entirely about DataSpark, not the hub. Suggest we cut.] The RI DataHUB is a key resource for cross-agency data projects such as the Rhode Island Talent Dashboard, an interactive site that demonstrates linkages between K-12, Postsecondary Education, and Workforce and enables policymakers and stakeholders to track student performance over time, assist agencies in evaluating program performance, answer questions across systems, and better communicate outcomes related to education and workforce programs.

Along with data infrastructure and data products, the RI DataHUB helps build strategic partnerships to support continued data integration in RI. Through the Governor’s State Data Strategy Initiative, we are working to help develop statewide data management and identify processes to enable more efficient, more secure uses of administrative data. Our knowledge about data governance has been tapped by this and other efforts.

The DataHUB is also a source of innovation on the technical aspects of data integration, including improvements to data linkage, data quality, and data documentation. Click the links below to access information on some of the cross-agency data integration efforts we’ve been involved in.

Enable Policy and Program Evaluation

The RI DataHUB has collaborated with the RI Department of Health, researchers from Brown University, the Urban Institute, HousingWorks RI, and many others to evaluate policy related to housing, adult education, school-based interventions, and childhood lead poisoning. Unlike researcher-led projects, policy and program evaluation help to assess support and compliance with existing policies and programs, identify gaps or overlaps in implementation, demonstrate the impacts and value of a policy or program, and provide accountability for resources invested by states or organizations. The findings feed directly back to decision-makers.

As an SLDS, the RI DataHUB can uniquely support such efforts because newly-collected data can be merged with existing administrative records for more cost-effective “quasi-experimental” analyses.

Past projects have included analyses of academic outcomes for various types of school-based interventions, such as after-school, college readiness, or restorative justice programming; investigations into access to early education services among children from disadvantaged populations; and tracking the college majors selected by Rhode Islanders according to their high school preparedness in computer science.

fields.title: Requesting Data Overview
fields.content:
Individual-Level Data Requests

A Data Use Agreement is required for any individual-level, de-identified data request to ensure that data are used in accordance with state and federal law. Once Data Use Agreements have been executed and contracts established, DataSpark will begin preparing your data. Legal documents and data preparation can take up to 6 months to execute, depending on the complexity of the request and DataSpark’s current project queue.

Aggregate-Level Data Requests

No Data Use Agreement needed, although agency review of outgoing aggregate data is part of the process. The data preparation could take up to 2 weeks to complete, potentially longer depending on the DataSpark current queue.

Forms and Policies

Acceptable Use Policy (link to PDF)

The Acceptable Use Policy outlines the conditions under which different types of access will be granted to different types of users (including DataHUB staff).

Data Request Policy (link to PDF)

The Data Request Policy outlines the responsibilities that requestors assume when obtaining individual-level de-identified data from the RI DataHUB.

Data Request

As the first step in requesting data, this form must be filled out and submitted to DataSpark.


Data Request Intake Form

DataSpark Data Services Agreement (link to PDF)

DataSpark operates under a cost-recovery model and charges for its services at a blended hourly rate. Requestors are not charged for DataSpark’s time to scope out requests and obtain preliminary approval from data providers to proceed with the request.

University of Rhode Island Data Use Agreement Template (Research Institution version)

Costs

The DataHUB’s funding comes from federal, state, local, and foundation grants and contracts. DataSpark, which manages the DataHUB, operates on a fee for service model. DataSpark is as a Service Center per the University of Rhode Island Office of the Controller Policy 97-03. Its office is located at the Robert L. Carothers Library and Learning Commons, 15 Lippitt Road, Kingston, RI 02881. The service center billing rate is calculated by dividing all annual costs required to operate the service center by total annual billable hours. The rate for fiscal year beginning July 1, 2019 and ending June 30, 2020 is $100 per hour. All DataSpark employees are billed at the same rate; the rate is subject to periodic review and may change.

fields.title: Research Projects
fields.content:
POSTSECONDARY OUTCOMES FOR RHODE ISLAND WORKFORCE TRAINING PARTICIPANTS

This analysis focuses on workforce training program participants and their entry into postsecondary education. It assesses participants by the timing of their postsecondary enrollment and their training exit type and determines how many participants enter fields of study that are preparatory for the same industries they accessed in their workforce training program.

Sources: RIOPC, RI DLT 10 April, 2020

HEALTH GRADS IN THE RI WORKFORCE

What is the employment landscape for health field graduates from RI's public higher education system?

Sources: RI DLT 10 April, 2020

PREPARING WORKERS FOR RI'S HIGH DEMAND OCCUPATIONS

What do our higher education and workforce data show about RI's production of skilled workers and whether they are filling high-demand occupations?

Sources: RIOPC, RI DLT 10 April, 2020
